 Handicap]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">9</span>1m1f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Emerilo\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|10}}\t\n|2nd\n|Jubilee Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|Sovereign Ruler\n|[[Kempton_Park_Racecourse|Kempton Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|31}}\t\n|6th\n|[[Lockinge Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|[[Habitat (horse)|Habitat]]\n|[[Newbury_Racecourse|Newbury]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|6|17}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Prince of Wales's Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Connaught (horse)|Connaught]]\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|7|5}}\t\n|1st\n|[[Eclipse Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Park Top]]\n|[[Sandown Park Racecourse|Sandown Park]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Stud career==\nWhen owner [[Hope Goddard Iselin]] retired at the age of 102, the horses she still had in training were sent to be sold at Newmarket. The one exception was Wolver Hollow who was given to his former trainer [[Cecil Boyd-Rochfort]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On Wolver Hollow's retirement, he was syndicated by the Curragh Bloodstock Agency and initially stood at Athgarvan Stud, The Curragh.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=999}}</ref> Through a friendship between Boyd-Rochfort and Billy Iceton, Wolver Hollow spent his latter breeding career at Tara Stud in County Meath.<ref>Griffiths, Richard. \"Tributes paid after death of renowned stud master Billy Iceton, aged 81.\" Racing Post, May 20, 2010: 17.</ref> Wolver Hollow enjoyed success with his first crop, spearheaded by the classic winning [[Furry Glen]]. His greatest achievement as a stallion came in 1976 when the Henry Cecil trained [[Wollow]] won five top class races, enabling his sire to become the leading sire in the UK and Ireland. Wollow's contribution to this achievement can not be understated. Wolver Hollow earned his accolade with a record of 34 wins from 18 horses amassing \u00a3192,362 in prize money - \u00a3166,389 of which was won by Wollow. Indeed, Wollow's earnings were such that they eclipsed the \u00a3166,323 earned by the progeny of [[Vaguely Noble]], that season's second leading sire.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=825}}</ref> Unsurprisingly, this would represent the zenith of Wolver Hollow's stallion career and while he would produce a further handful of useful horses, none of them would win at the highest level. \n\nAs a damsire, Wolver Hollow could not count any European Group One winners among his descendants although Love A Show was victorious in the 1983 [[Blue Diamond Stakes]]. Other horses of note include Reach, winner of the 1984 [[Royal Lodge Stakes]], Festive Cheer, third in the 1991 [[Phoenix Stakes]], Treasure Hope, winner of the 1992 [[Premio Regina Elena]] (Italian 1000 Guineas), and Wrapping, a runner up in the 1989 [[Oaks d'Italia]]. Wolver Hollow was also the damsire of several useful [[National Hunt]] horses such as Simply Dashing, a high class handicap chaser who finished second in a [[Charlie Hall Chase]], 1992 [[Baring Bingham Novices' Hurdle]] winner Thetford Forest and useful handicapper Latent Talent. \n\nHe was euthanised due to deteriorating health on 13 June 1987.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pedigreequery.com/wolver+hollow|title=Wolver Hollow Horse Pedigree|website=www.pedigreequery.com}}</ref>\n\n===Notable progeny===\n\n''c = [[colt (horse)|colt]], f = [[filly]], g = [[gelding]]''\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse\" font-size:80%\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Foaled'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Name'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Dam'''\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Sex'''\n| style=\"width:510px;\"| '''Major Wins and Notable Performances'''\n|-\n| 1971\n| Charlie Bubbles\n| Sixandahalf\n| c\n| 1st [[Hardwicke Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| [[Furry Glen]]\n| Cleftess\n| c\n| 1st [[Marble Hill Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Leopardstown Stakes|Mullion Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Irish 2000 Guineas]] (1974) 1st [[International Stakes (Ireland)|Whitehall Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Vauxhall Trial Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Gallinule Stakes]] (1974) 3rd [[Coventry Stakes]] (1973) 3rd Larkspur Stakes (1973) \n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| Wanlockhead\n| Exultation\n| c\n| 3rd [[Gordon Richards Stakes|Westbury Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| [[Wollow]]\n| Wichuraiana\n| c\n| 1st [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Dewhurst Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Greenham Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[2000 Guineas]] (1976) 1st [[Eclipse Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[Sussex Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[International Stakes|Benson & Hedges Gold Cup]] (1976)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| Wolverlife\n| Miralife\n| c\n| 3rd [[Duke of York Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Palace House Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Diamond Jubilee Stakes|Cork and Orrery Stakes]]\n|-\n|-\n| 1975\n| My Hollow\n| Saucy Mine\n| f\n| 1st [[Royal Whip Stakes]] (1980) 1st [[Desmond Stakes]] (1980) 2nd [[Blandford Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Galaxy Libra\n| Garden of Eden\n| c\n| 1st [[Man o' War Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Joe Hirsch Turf Classic Invitational Stakes]] (1981) 3rd [[Charles Whittingham Stakes|Hollywood Invitational Handicap]] (1981) 3rd [[Washington, D.C. International Stakes]] (1981)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Wolverton\n| Mary Murphy\n| c\n| 1st [[Prix Daniel Wildenstein|Prix du Rond-Point]] (1979) 1st [[Prix Edmond Blanc]] (1980) 2nd [[Prix Greffulhe]] (1979)\n|-\n|-\n| 1977\n| Gift Wrapped\n| Doc Nan\n| f\n| 1st [[Lingfield Oaks Trial]] (1980) 2nd [[Musidora Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Sun Chariot Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Hays\n| Sing A Song\n| c\n| 1st [[Mill Reef Stakes]] (1981) 1st [[2,000 Guineas Trial Stakes]] (1982) 2nd [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Hungerford Stakes]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Teofane\n| The Yellow Girl\n| c\n| 2nd [[Derby Italiano]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1980\n| Sherbaz\n| Shelina\n| c\n| 3rd [[Prix La Rochette]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1981\n| Gamelion\n| Glamingo\n| g\n| 1st Prix des Drags (1986)\n|-\n|-\n| 1983\n| Hollow Hand\n| Fingers\n| c\n| 2nd [[Horris Hill Stakes]] (1985)\n|-\n|}\n\n==Pedigree==\n{{Pedigree\n|name = Wolver Hollow (GB), bay horse, 1964<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|inf =\n|f = Sovereign Path (GB)<br />1956\n|m = Cygnet (GB)<br />1950\n|ff = [[Grey Sovereign]] (GB)<br />1948\n|fm = Mountain Path (GB)<br />1948\n|mf = [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]] (FR)<br />1942\n|mm = Mrs. Swan Song (IRE)<br />1940\n|fff = [[Nasrullah (horse)|Nasrullah]]\n|ffm = Kong\n|fmf = Bobsleigh\n|fmm = Path Of Peace\n|mff = [[Tourbillon (horse)|Tourbillon]]\n|mfm = Astronomie\n|mmf = Sir Walter Raleigh\n|mmm = Donati's Comet\n|ffff = [[Nearco]]\n|fffm = Mumtaz Begum\n|ffmf = Baytown\n|ffmm = Clang\n|fmff = [[Gainsborough (horse)|Gainsborough]]\n|fmfm = Toboggan\n|fmmf = Winalot\n|fmmm = Grand Peace\n|mfff = [[Ksar (horse)|Ksar]]\n|mffm = Durban\n|mfmf = Asterus\n|mfmm = Likka\n|mmff = Prince Galahad\n|mmfm = Smoke Lass\n|mmmf = Flying Orb\n|mmmm = Sunshot\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKvNyOYoSS0 1969 Eclipse Stakes] (YouTube)\n\n[[Category:1964 racehorse births]]\n[[Category:1987 racehorse deaths]]\n[[Category:Racehorses bred in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Thoroughbred family 19-b]]\n[[Category:British Champion Thoroughbred Sires]]\n[[Category:Racehorses trained in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British Thoroughbred racehorse}}\n{{Infobox racehorse\n| horsename = Wolver Hollow\n| image = Owner_Mrs_C_Iselin.svg\n| caption = Colours of [[Hope Goddard Iselin|Mrs C. O. Iselin]]\n| sire = Sovereign Path\n| grandsire = [[Grey Sovereign]]\n| dam = [[Cygnet (horse)|Cygnet]]\n| damsire = [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]]\n| sex = [[Stallion (horse)|Stallion]]\n| foaled = 1964\n| country =  [[United Kingdom]]\n| colour = [[Bay (horse)|Bay]]\n| breeder = \n| owner = [[Hope Goddard Iselin]]\n| trainer = [[Cecil Boyd-Rochfort]]<br>[[Henry Cecil]]\n| record = 20: 4-5-3\n| earnings = \u00a340,546\n| race = [[Eclipse Stakes]] (1969)\n| awards = [[Leading sire in Great Britain and Ireland]] (1976)\n| honours =  [[Timeform|Timeform rating]]: 126 \n| updated= \n}}\n'''Wolver Hollow''' (1964\u20131987) was a British-bred [[Thoroughbred]] [[Horse racing|racehorse]] and stallion. In a career spanning four seasons, his performances in handicaps and top class company, including victory in the 1969 [[Eclipse Stakes]], established him as a talented racehorse without being exceptional. He would achieve greater success as a stallion whereupon retiring to stud where he became [[Leading sire in Great Britain and Ireland|Champion Sire]] in Britain.\n\n==Background==\n\nBy Sovereign Path and out of Cygnet, Wolver Hollow was sold as a yearling, fetching 4,000 guineas<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Wolver Hollow shows his class.\" Times, September 8, 1967, 14. The Times Digital Archive (accessed April 3, 2020).</ref> Sovereign Path, rated 125 by [[Timeform]],<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=701}}</ref> was successful in the 1959 [[Tetrarch Stakes]] as well as the 1960 renewals of the [[Lockinge Stakes]] and [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]. As a sire, he produced sixteen crops of racehorses, the most notable of which was [[Humble Duty]]. Nevertheless, he also counted multiple big race winners among his progeny including Town Crier ([[Queen Anne Stakes]]), Supreme Sovereign ([[Lockinge Stakes]]) and Spanish Express ([[Middle Park Stakes]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=936}}</ref>. While Wolver Hollow's dam Cygnet, by undefeated champion racehorse [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]], did not hail from an immediately prolific family, her third dam, Sunshot, was the granddam of classic winners Resplendent (1926 [[Irish Oaks]] and dam of [[Windsor Lad]]) and Sol Speranza who won the same two classics in 1937.<ref>{{cite journal |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=1943 |title=Bloodstock Breeders Annual Review |url= |journal=Bloodstock Breeders Annual Review |volume=32 |issue= |pages=73 |doi= |access-date=}}</ref> Alongside Wolver Hollow, Cygnet produced nine other foals including Gaybrook Swan, second in the 1970 [[Northern Dancer Turf Stakes|Niagara Handicap]] and Tall Dream, runner up in both the [[Vincent O'Brien National Stakes|National Stakes]] and [[Beresford Stakes]] of 1971.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloodstockreports.co.uk/weatherbys/wbr/orderreports/orderReportParameters.jsp?listSection=FR&listSectionName=Free%20Reports&countryCode=GB&optNo=79&priceId=1 |title=Weatherbys Bloodstock Reports |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://galopp-sieger.de/galoppsieger/pferd_html?pschl=Tall%20DreamTamerlane |title=Gallop Sieger |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date= |quote=}}</ref>\n\n==Racing career==\n\n===1966: two-year-old season===\nWolver Hollow made his debut in the 1966 New Stakes, now known as the [[Norfolk Stakes (Great Britain)|Norfolk Stakes]], at Ascot where he finished four lengths behind the Johnson Houghton trained Falcon.<ref>FROM OUR RACING CORRESPONDENT. \"Fighting Charlie falters but wins easily.\" Times, June 17, 1966, 5.</ref> On his second start, he finished behind Falcon again when fourth in the [[National Stakes (Sandown Park)|National Stakes]] at Sandown<ref>\"Sandown Park Details\" Times, 21 July 1966, p. 5.</ref> - a course incidentally where Falcon would win the following season's [[Temple Stakes]]. Wolver Hollow would then be unplaced at Kempton before rounding off the season finishing fourth of thirteen starters in the [[Dewhurst Stakes]] behind the next season's English and Irish Derby third Dart Board.\n\n===1967: three-year-old season===\nNewbury would be Wolver Hollow's first port of call in 1967 where he would contest the [[Greenham Stakes]], a traditional trial for the [[2000 Guineas]]. Finishing third by a neck and a head, this was the closest he had come to shedding his maiden tag. However, it was not the strongest Guineas trial given that neither of the front two were entered for the classic.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Classic horses not impressive.\" Times, April 24, 1967, 12.</ref> While it transpired to be useful form, (the runner up,[[Reform (horse)|Reform]], would become the leading miler of the season), Wolver Hollow started at an unfancied 40/1 when finishing unplaced on his next start in the Guineas.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Royal Palace beats milers at their own game.\" Times, May 4, 1967, 13.</ref> Returning to the Royal Ascot meeting where he made his debut the previous year, Wolver Hollow again ran into Reform finishing just under a length and a half fourth in the [[St James's Palace Stakes]].<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Steeple Aston can go one better in Hunt Cup.\" Times, 21 June 1967, p. 11.</ref> At the Goodwood meeting, Wolver Hollow entered handicap company with a reasonable fifth under second top-weight, giving a pound to Irish Derby runner up Sucaryl and six pounds to [[Falmouth Stakes]] winner Resilience.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Hopes vanish as Caergwrle heads for Midhurst.\" Times, 29 July 1967, p. 14.</ref> A step down in class a month later facilitated Wolver Hollow finally losing his maiden tag as he won the ten furlong Virginia Stakes at Newcastle. While the contest was effectively a maiden race, Wolver Hollow only had to be shaken up to win by four lengths.<ref>SNOW, JIM. \"Northern Racing.\" Times, August 29, 1967, 11.</ref> Little over a week later, Wolver Hollow doubled his tally with success in the one mile Crathorne Sweepstakes at York. There he faced three rivals;- Worthy Friend, a long priced outsider, [[Epsom Derby|Derby]] also-ran Scottish Sinbad who won a handicap at the same Newcastle meeting where Wolver Hollow was victorious, and [[Queen Anne Stakes]] runner up Arenaria who was in receipt of ten pounds.<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Scottish Sinbad is best choice.\" Times, 7 Sept. 1967, p. 14.</ref> Scottish Sinbad made the running but was closely tracked by Wolver Hollow under a motionless Edward Hide who sent his mount home inside the final furlong to win by a length and a half with Arenaria a further two lengths behind. After the race, he was given a 25/1 quote for the [[Cambridgeshire Handicap]].<ref>SNOW,, JIM. \"Wolver Hollow shows his class.\" Times, September 8, 1967, p. 14.</ref> In preparation for the Cambridgeshire, Wolver Hollow contested the Wavertree Stakes at Newmarket but was unable to complete a hat-trick, finishing a length and three quarters behind easy [[Nassau Stakes]] winner Fair Winter.<ref>\"Saturday's racing results\" Times, September 18, 1967, p. 11.</ref> Wolver Hollow capped off his season with a two and a half length third in the Cambridgeshire off 8st 12lb behind [[Irish 1,000 Guineas]] winner Lacquer<ref>\"Saturday's racing results\" Times, September 28, 1967, p. 12.</ref>\n\n===1968: four-year-old season===\nWolver Hollow made four racecourse appearances in 1968 although the first was not until August when he participated in two races at the Deauville summer festival. The first appearance came when fourth in the [[Prix Gontaut-Biron]] won by Frontal - himself fourth in the previous season's [[Prix du Jockey Club]]. On ground considered too soft for him, he was squeezed out of third by a head by Grandier who went on to win a [[Prix d'Ispahan]] and a [[Prix Ganay]] as well as finish third in a [[Prix de l'Arc de Triomphe]].<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Rehearsal for Hopeful Venture.\" Times, 26 Aug. 1968, p. 12.</ref> Nine days later, Wolver Hollow ventured into calmer waters when winning the Prix Ridgway from Right Honourable and Atopolis. <ref>PAR, R. R. \"\" WOLVER HOLLOW \"REMPORTE LE PRIX RIDGWAY.\" Le Monde, 28 Aug. 1968.</ref> After a scheduled run at Newbury was cancelled following the abandonment of the meeting, Wolver Hollow's next run was in the [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]<ref>\"Racing Results.\" Times, 16 Sept. 1968, p. 12.</ref>. The absences of [[2000 Guineas]] third Jimmy Reppin and [[Irish Derby]] runner up Ribofilio notwithstanding, the field still featured [[Sussex Stakes]] runner up World Cup, [[Prix Jean Prat]] victor Lorenzaccio and [[Greenham Stakes]] winner Heathen.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Lorenzaccio can hold off World Cup.\" Times, September 28, 1968, p. 6.</ref> The race, ran on soft ground, was contested between World Cup and Wolver Hollow up the straight with the former eventually winning by four easy lengths with Lorenzaccio a further three lengths behind in third.<ref>BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"World Cup Scores Despite Rumours.\" The Observer, Sep 29, 1968.</ref> Wolver Hollow's season would culminate once again in the Cambridgeshire Handicap, this time shouldering top weight of 9st 8lbs. Next in the weights was [[Diadem Stakes]] winner Secret Ray on 9st 6lbs, [[Jersey Stakes]] third Paddy Me on 9st 4lbs, the same weight as previous year's runner up Straight Master while [[Yorkshire Oaks]] winner Exchange, carrying 9st, was sent off favourite.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Sir Ivor has stamina to win 'Champion'.\" Times, 19 Oct. 1968, p. 7.</ref> Wolver Hollow ran a career best to finish second, going down by a neck to Emirilo despite conceding twenty-seven pounds.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Great win for Sir Ivor at Newmarket.\" Times, 21 Oct. 1968, p. 11.</ref>\n\n===1969: five-year-old season===\n[[Henry Cecil|Henry Cecil's]] first season as a racehorse trainer would be spearheaded by Wolver Hollow's final season as a racehorse. His reappearance came in the Mark Lane Jubilee Stakes, a ten furlong handicap over ten furlongs on very soft ground. There he faced a stiff task sitting on top of the handicap conceding upwards of seven pounds to winners of the [[Rosebery Stakes]] and the [[City and Suburban Handicap]] along with the previous year's winner.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Wolver Hollow can survive stern test.\" Times, May 10, 1969, 6.</ref> In the event, bottom weight Sovereign Ruler won by a facile eight lengths and would go on to win two and twice finish placed in valuable handicaps through the rest of the season.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=671}}</ref> Wolver Hollow finished runner up while conceding thirty-five pounds to the well handicapped winner and was very much considered a contender going into the [[Lockinge Stakes]] on his next start.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Jimmy Reppin may take Lockinge Stakes.\" Times, 31 May 1969, p. 6.</ref> However, he would finish a tailed off last of six behind [[Habitat (horse)|Habitat]] and subsequently underwent a dope test.<ref>BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"Lockinge Goes to Habitat.\" The Observer, Jun 01, 1969. P. 21.</ref> Wolver Hollow's penultimate start came at Royal Ascot in the [[Prince of Wales's Stakes]] where he would be ridden by [[Lester Piggot]] for the first time. Here he faced four rivals in the shape of [[Noel Murless|Noel Murless's]] top class [[Connaught (horse)|Connaught]], [[Epsom Derby]] also-ran Stoned and a couple of high class handicappers.<ref>PHILLIPS, MICHAEL. \"Prince Tenderfoot may be too fast for rivals.\" Times, 17 June 1969, p. 13.</ref> Class told with Connaught making all to win by five lengths ahead of Wolver Hollow, with stoned a further two lengths behind in third.<ref>SNOW, JIM. \"Double for Barclay.\" Times, June 18, 1969, 13.</ref> Wolver Hollow's career would be defined by his final start in the [[Eclipse Stakes]] where he would also be the last horse to carry his owner's colours.<ref name=\"auto1\">BAERLEIN, RICHARD. \"Big Prize for Last Runner.\" The Observer (1901- 2003), Jul 06, 1969, p. 19.</ref> Coughing forced Connaught and Ribofilio (Irish Derby second) to miss their engagement while the useful Remand was withdrawn leaving seven runners to face the starter at Sandown. High class continental form was well represented with Light Wind, who had won that season's [[Premio Presidente della Repubblica]], Hogarth who won the 1968 [[Derby Italiano]] and Timmy My Boy who finished runner up in that year's [[Prix du Jockey Club]]. Royal Rocket was third in the [[Brigadier Gerard Stakes|Coronation Stakes]] while sole three year old runner Rocked finished third in the [[Greenham Stakes]]. Park Top, bidding to become the first mare to win in the race's history, came into the race three from three for the season collecting the Prix de la Seine, the [[Coronation Cup]] and the [[Hardwicke Stakes]] along the way.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=509}}</ref>. Waiting tactics were typically employed on Park Top and controversially, this would be her undoing in the race. As described in Timeform's Racehorses of 1969 \"Wolver Hollow turned for home behind Park Top, came up the rails, gradually made his way to the front after an uninterrupted run, and led throughout the last furlong to win comfortably. Park Top, on the other hand, had several positions in the straight. She ran into the heels of the pacemaking Rocked two furlongs out, and after making her way round that horse she found her way blocked by the Italian Derby winner Hogarth. By the time she had moved out to come round Hogarth on the wide outside she had no chance of catching Wolver Hollow: she had used up most of her energy finding a way through, and courage wasn't enough to win her the prize.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=510}}</ref> Park Top would win the [[King George VI and Queen Elizabeth Stakes]] next time under Lester Piggot, confirming that she was superior to her Sandown showing. Nevertheless, Wolver Hollow's win was enough to secure a new career as a stallion.\n\n==Races==\n\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\" | border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" style=\" text-align:centre; margin-left:1em; float:centre ;border-collapse: collapse; font-size:100%\"\n|-  style=\"background:#dacaa4; text-align:center;\"\n!'''Date'''\n!'''Finish'''\n!'''Race'''\n!'''Dist'''\n!'''Jockey'''\n!'''Winner/Runner up '''\n!'''Track'''\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|06|16}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Norfolk Stakes (Great Britain)|New Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>5f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Falcon\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|07|20}}\t\n|4th\n|[[National_Stakes_(Sandown_Park)|National Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">5</span>5f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Falcon\n|[[Sandown Park Racecourse|Sandown Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|09|17}}\t\n|Unplaced\n|Imperial Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">6</span>6f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Heath Rose\n|[[Kempton_Park_Racecourse|Kempton Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1966|10|14}}\t\n|4th\n|[[Dewhurst Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">7</span>7f\n|Stan Clayton\n|Dart Board\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|04|22}}\t\n|3rd\n|[[Greenham Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">7</span>7f\n|[[Doug Smith (jockey)|Doug Smith]]\n|Play High\n|[[Newbury_Racecourse|Newbury]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|05|03}}\t\n|Unplaced\n|[[2000 Guineas Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Doug Smith  (jockey)|Doug Smith ]]\n|[[Royal_Palace_(horse)|Royal Palace]]\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|06|20}}\t\n|4th\n|[[St James's Palace Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[George Moore (jockey)|George Moore]]\n|[[Reform (horse)|Reform]]\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|07|28}}\t\n|5th\n|News of the World Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|Sucaryl\n|[[Goodwood Racecourse|Goodwood]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|08|28}}\t\n|1st\n|Virginia Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Edward Hide]]\n|Future Fame\n|[[Newcastle Racecourse|Newcastle]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|09|07}}\t\n|1st\n|Crathorne Sweepstakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Edward Hide]]\n|Scottish Sinbad\n|[[York Racecourse|York]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|09|16}}\t\n|3rd\n|Wavertree Sweepstakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Doug Smith (jockey)|Doug Smith]]\n|Fair Winter\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1967|10|21}}\t\n|3rd\n|[[Cambridgeshire Handicap]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">9</span>1m1f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Lacquer\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|8|17}}\t\n|4th\n|[[Prix Gontaut-Biron]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Frontal\n|[[Deauville-La Touques Racecourse|Deauville]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|8|26}}\t\n|1st\n|Prix Ridgway\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Right Honourable\n|[[Deauville-La Touques Racecourse|Deauville]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|9|28}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|World Cup\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1968|10|19}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Cambridgeshire Handicap]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">9</span>1m1f\n|[[Scobie Breasley]]\n|Emerilo\n|[[Newmarket_Racecourse|Newmarket]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|10}}\t\n|2nd\n|Jubilee Stakes\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|Sovereign Ruler\n|[[Kempton_Park_Racecourse|Kempton Park]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|5|31}}\t\n|6th\n|[[Lockinge Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">8</span>1m\n|Jimmy Lindley\n|[[Habitat (horse)|Habitat]]\n|[[Newbury_Racecourse|Newbury]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|6|17}}\t\n|2nd\n|[[Prince of Wales's Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Connaught (horse)|Connaught]]\n|[[Ascot Racecourse|Ascot]]\n|-\n|-\n| {{dts|format=dmy|1969|7|5}}\t\n|1st\n|[[Eclipse Stakes]]\n|<span style=\"display:none\">10</span>1m2f\n|[[Lester Piggott]]\n|[[Park Top]]\n|[[Sandown Park Racecourse|Sandown Park]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==Stud career==\nWhen owner [[Hope Goddard Iselin]] retired at the age of 102, the horses she still had in training were sent to be sold at Newmarket. The one exception was Wolver Hollow who was given to his former trainer [[Cecil Boyd-Rochfort]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> On Wolver Hollow's retirement, he was syndicated by the Curragh Bloodstock Agency and initially stood at Athgarvan Stud, The Curragh.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1970 |title=Racehorses of 1969|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=999}}</ref> Through a friendship between Boyd-Rochfort and Billy Iceton, Wolver Hollow spent his latter breeding career at Tara Stud in County Meath.<ref>Griffiths, Richard. \"Tributes paid after death of renowned stud master Billy Iceton, aged 81.\" Racing Post, May 20, 2010: 17.</ref> Wolver Hollow enjoyed success with his first crop, spearheaded by the classic winning [[Furry Glen]]. His greatest achievement as a stallion came in 1976 when the Henry Cecil trained [[Wollow]] won five top class races, enabling his sire to become the leading sire in the UK and Ireland. Wollow's contribution to this achievement can not be understated. Wolver Hollow earned his accolade with a record of 34 wins from 18 horses amassing \u00a3192,362 in prize money - \u00a3166,389 of which was won by Wollow. Indeed, Wollow's earnings were such that they eclipsed the \u00a3166,323 earned by the progeny of [[Vaguely Noble]], that season's second leading sire.<ref>{{cite book |last=Timeform |date=1977 |title=Racehorses of 1976|location=London |publisher=Portway Press Limited |page=825}}</ref> Unsurprisingly, this would represent the zenith of Wolver Hollow's stallion career and while he would produce a further handful of useful horses, none of them would win at the highest level. \n\nAs a damsire, Wolver Hollow could not count any European Group One winners among his descendants although Love A Show was victorious in the 1983 [[Blue Diamond Stakes]]. Other horses of note include Reach, winner of the 1984 [[Royal Lodge Stakes]], Festive Cheer, third in the 1991 [[Phoenix Stakes]], Treasure Hope, winner of the 1992 [[Premio Regina Elena]] (Italian 1000 Guineas), and Wrapping, a runner up in the 1989 [[Oaks d'Italia]]. Wolver Hollow was also the damsire of several useful [[National Hunt]] horses such as Simply Dashing, a high class handicap chaser who finished second in a [[Charlie Hall Chase]], 1992 [[Baring Bingham Novices' Hurdle]] winner Thetford Forest and useful handicapper Latent Talent. \n\nHe was euthanised due to deteriorating health on 13 June 1987.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pedigreequery.com/wolver+hollow|title=Wolver Hollow Horse Pedigree|website=www.pedigreequery.com}}</ref>\n\n===Notable progeny===\n\n''c = [[colt (horse)|colt]], f = [[filly]], g = [[gelding]]''\n\n{| border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse\" font-size:80%\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Foaled'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Name'''\n| style=\"width:120px;\"| '''Dam'''\n| style=\"width:35px;\"| '''Sex'''\n| style=\"width:510px;\"| '''Major Wins and Notable Performances'''\n|-\n| 1971\n| Charlie Bubbles\n| Sixandahalf\n| c\n| 1st [[Hardwicke Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| [[Furry Glen]]\n| Cleftess\n| c\n| 1st [[Marble Hill Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Leopardstown Stakes|Mullion Stakes]] (1973) 1st [[Irish 2000 Guineas]] (1974) 1st [[International Stakes (Ireland)|Whitehall Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Vauxhall Trial Stakes]] (1974) 2nd [[Gallinule Stakes]] (1974) 3rd [[Coventry Stakes]] (1973) 3rd Larkspur Stakes (1973) \n|-\n|-\n| 1971\n| Wanlockhead\n| Exultation\n| c\n| 3rd [[Gordon Richards Stakes|Westbury Stakes]] (1975)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| [[Wollow]]\n| Wichuraiana\n| c\n| 1st [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Dewhurst Stakes]] (1975) 1st [[Greenham Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[2000 Guineas]] (1976) 1st [[Eclipse Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[Sussex Stakes]] (1976) 1st [[International Stakes|Benson & Hedges Gold Cup]] (1976)\n|-\n|-\n| 1973\n| Wolverlife\n| Miralife\n| c\n| 3rd [[Duke of York Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Palace House Stakes]] (1977) 3rd [[Diamond Jubilee Stakes|Cork and Orrery Stakes]]\n|-\n|-\n| 1975\n| My Hollow\n| Saucy Mine\n| f\n| 1st [[Royal Whip Stakes]] (1980) 1st [[Desmond Stakes]] (1980) 2nd [[Blandford Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Galaxy Libra\n| Garden of Eden\n| c\n| 1st [[Man o' War Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Joe Hirsch Turf Classic Invitational Stakes]] (1981) 3rd [[Charles Whittingham Stakes|Hollywood Invitational Handicap]] (1981) 3rd [[Washington, D.C. International Stakes]] (1981)\n|-\n|-\n| 1976\n| Wolverton\n| Mary Murphy\n| c\n| 1st [[Prix Daniel Wildenstein|Prix du Rond-Point]] (1979) 1st [[Prix Edmond Blanc]] (1980) 2nd [[Prix Greffulhe]] (1979)\n|-\n|-\n| 1977\n| Gift Wrapped\n| Doc Nan\n| f\n| 1st [[Lingfield Oaks Trial]] (1980) 2nd [[Musidora Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Queen Elizabeth II Stakes]] (1980) 3rd [[Sun Chariot Stakes]] (1980)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Hays\n| Sing A Song\n| c\n| 1st [[Mill Reef Stakes]] (1981) 1st [[2,000 Guineas Trial Stakes]] (1982) 2nd [[Champagne Stakes (Great Britain)|Champagne Stakes]] (1981) 2nd [[Hungerford Stakes]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1979\n| Teofane\n| The Yellow Girl\n| c\n| 2nd [[Derby Italiano]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1980\n| Sherbaz\n| Shelina\n| c\n| 3rd [[Prix La Rochette]] (1982)\n|-\n|-\n| 1981\n| Gamelion\n| Glamingo\n| g\n| 1st Prix des Drags (1986)\n|-\n|-\n| 1983\n| Hollow Hand\n| Fingers\n| c\n| 2nd [[Horris Hill Stakes]] (1985)\n|-\n|}\n\n==Pedigree==\n{{Pedigree\n|name = Wolver Hollow (GB), bay horse, 1964<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|inf =\n|f = Sovereign Path (GB)<br />1956\n|m = Cygnet (GB)<br />1950\n|ff = [[Grey Sovereign]] (GB)<br />1948\n|fm = Mountain Path (GB)<br />1948\n|mf = [[Caracalla (horse)|Caracalla]] (FR)<br />1942\n|mm = Mrs. Swan Song (IRE)<br />1940\n|fff = [[Nasrullah (horse)|Nasrullah]]\n|ffm = Kong\n|fmf = Bobsleigh\n|fmm = Path Of Peace\n|mff = [[Tourbillon (horse)|Tourbillon]]\n|mfm = Astronomie\n|mmf = Sir Walter Raleigh\n|mmm = Donati's Comet\n|ffff = [[Nearco]]\n|fffm = Mumtaz Begum\n|ffmf = Baytown\n|ffmm = Clang\n|fmff = [[Gainsborough (horse)|Gainsborough]]\n|fmfm = Toboggan\n|fmmf = Winalot\n|fmmm = Grand Peace\n|mfff = [[Ksar (horse)|Ksar]]\n|mffm = Durban\n|mfmf = Asterus\n|mfmm = Likka\n|mmff = Prince Galahad\n|mmfm = Smoke Lass\n|mmmf = Flying Orb\n|mmmm = Sunshot\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FKvNyOYoSS0 1969 Eclipse Stakes] (YouTube)\n\n[[Category:1964 racehorse births]]\n[[Category:1987 racehorse deaths]]\n[[Category:Racehorses bred in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Thoroughbred family 19-b]]\n[[Category:British Champion Thoroughbred Sires]]\n[[Category:Racehorses trained in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Jair du Cochet", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolver_Hollow"}
{"title_page": "Charlene Fernetz", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian former actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}{{Infobox person\n| name = Charlene Fernetz\n| image = \n| birthname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1960|3|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Saskatchewan]], Canada \n| occupation = Actress\n| yearsactive = 1991\u20132008\n| spouse = Peter Mora\n| partner = \n| parents = Ken and Carmelita Fernetz\n| website = \n| awards = Best Actress<br>2005 ''Seeking Fear''\n}}\n\n'''Charlene Fernetz''' (born March 23, 1960) is a Canadian former [[actress]].\n\n==Life and career==\nFernetz was born on a large farm in the middle of [[Saskatchewan]], Canada and studied Journalism at the [[British Columbia Institute of Technology]]; but in 1990 it was while doing regional theater in [[Portland, Oregon]], that she caught the eye of a Manager from [[Los Angeles]], and within months she was a guest on the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series, ''[[Kurt Vonnegut's Monkey House]]''.\n\n==Filmography==\n*''[[Mann & Machine]]'' (1996) as Yvonne Stepka\n*''[[The Hat Squad]]'' (1992)\n*''[[Street Justice]]'' (1991\u20131993) as Malloy\n*''[[Made in America (1993 film)|Made in America]]'' (1993) as Paula\n*''[[Woman on the Ledge]]'' (1993) as Carol\n*''[[Harmony Cats]]'' (1993) as Jane Pitkeithly\n*''[[Heads (film)|Heads]]'' (1993) as Betty Jo\n*''[[The Mighty Jungle]]'' (1994) as Susan Winfield\n*''[[Paris or Somewhere]]'' (1994) as Gwen\n*''[[Kung Fu: The Legend Continues]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Hawkeye (1994 TV series)|Hawkeye (TV series)]]'' (1995) as Hester\n*''[[Sabrina the Teenage Witch (film)|Sabrina the Teenage Witch]]'' (1996) as Aunt Zelda<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2016/09/27/20-things-you-may-not-know-about-sabrina-the-teenage-witch-6124369/|title=20 things you may not know about Sabrina, The Teenage Witch|date=2016-09-27|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-04-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=O'Connor|first=John J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/04/10/arts/tele