{"title_page": "Andreas Veerpalu", "text_new": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = Andreas Veerpalu\n| nickname       =\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| image_size     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|5|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Otep\u00e4\u00e4]], Estonia\n| residence      = \n| country        = {{EST}}\n| sport          = [[Cross country skiing]] \n| event          = \n| alma_mater     = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height \t = \n| weight \t = \n| club           = \n| pb             = \n| website        = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Andreas Veerpalu ''' (born 24 May 1994) is an Estonian [[Cross country skiing|cross country skier]] who competes internationally.<ref>[https://data.fis-ski.com/dynamic/athlete-biography.html?sector=CC&listid=&competitorid=167214 FIS profile ]</ref>\n \nHe represented Estonia at the [[2018 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/OWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/athlete-profile-n3043292-andreas-veerpalu.htm |title=Athletic profile - Andreas Veerpalu  |website=PyeongChang2018.com |publisher=[[PyeongChang Organizing Committee for the 2018 Olympic & Paralympic Winter Games]] |accessdate=11 February 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420072424/https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/OWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/athlete-profile-n3043292-andreas-veerpalu.htm |archivedate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2019, during the [[FIS Nordic World Ski Championships 2019]], Veerpalu was arrested along with four other skiers, Estonia's [[Karel Tammj\u00e4rv]], Kazakhstan's [[Alexey Poltoranin]] and Austrians [[Max Hauke]] and [[Dominik Baldauf]], on suspicion of using [[blood doping]] assisted by German sports doctor Mark Schmidt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Two Estonian skiers held in Austria world championships doping probe |url=https://news.err.ee/914922/two-estonian-skiers-held-in-austria-world-championships-doping-probe |publisher=[[Estonian Public Broadcasting|ERR]] |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> On release from police custody both Estonians admitted using blood doping.<ref>{{cite web |title=Estonian skiers released from police custody in Austria, confirm doping probe |url=https://news.postimees.ee/6535234/estonian-skiers-released-from-police-custody-in-austria-confirm-doping-probe |publisher=[[Postimees]] |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nAndreas is the son of former Estonian cross-country skier, [[Andrus Veerpalu]]. His sister Anette is also a cross-country skier for Estonia.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veerpalu, Andreas}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Otep\u00e4\u00e4]]\n[[Category:Estonian male cross-country skiers]]\n[[Category:Estonian sportspeople in doping cases]]\n[[Category:Olympic cross-country skiers of Estonia]]\n[[Category:Cross-country skiers at the 2018 Winter Olympics]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 2012 Winter Youth Olympics]]\n[[Category:Doping cases in cross-country skiing]]\n\n\n{{Estonia-crosscountry-skiing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = Andreas Veerpalu\n| nickname       =\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| image_size     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1994|5|24|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Otep\u00e4\u00e4]], Estonia\n| residence      = \n| country        = {{EST}}\n| sport          = [[Cross country skiing]] \n| event          = \n| alma_mater     = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height \t = \n| weight \t = \n| club           = \n| pb             = \n| website        = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Andreas Veerpalu ''' (born 24 May 1994) is an Estonian [[Cross country skiing|cross country skier]] who competes internationally.<ref>[https://data.fis-ski.com/dynamic/athlete-biography.html?sector=CC&listid=&competitorid=167214 FIS profile ]</ref>\n \nHe represented Estonia at the [[2018 Winter Olympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/OWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/athlete-profile-n3043292-andreas-veerpalu.htm |title=Athletic profile - Andreas Veerpalu  |website=PyeongChang2018.com |publisher=[[PyeongChang Organizing Committee for the 2018 Olympic & Paralympic Winter Games]] |accessdate=11 February 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420072424/https://www.pyeongchang2018.com/en/game-time/results/OWG2018/en/cross-country-skiing/athlete-profile-n3043292-andreas-veerpalu.htm |archivedate=2018-04-20}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 February 2019, during the [[FIS Nordic World Ski Championships 2019]], Veerpalu was arrested along with four other skiers, Estonia's [[Karel Tammj\u00e4rv]], Kazakhstan's [[Alexey Poltoranin]] and Austrians [[Max Hauke]] and [[Dominik Baldauf]], on suspicion of using [[blood doping]] assisted by German sports doctor Mark Schmidt.<ref>{{cite web |title=Two Estonian skiers held in Austria world championships doping probe |url=https://news.err.ee/914922/two-estonian-skiers-held-in-austria-world-championships-doping-probe |publisher=[[Estonian Public Broadcasting|ERR]] |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> On release from police custody both Estonians admitted using blood doping.<ref>{{cite web |title=Estonian skiers released from police custody in Austria, confirm doping probe |url=https://news.postimees.ee/6535234/estonian-skiers-released-from-police-custody-in-austria-confirm-doping-probe |publisher=[[Postimees]] |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal==\nAndreas is the son of former Estonian cross-country skier, [[Andrus Veerpalu]]. His sister [[Anette Veerpalu]] is also a cross-country skier for Estonia.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Veerpalu, Andreas}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Otep\u00